{"source_key":"sha256-3f4607c5fc467aa4a903804a986bb8ed","record_index":344,"record_hash":"sha256:d0bac51010ac4fe56ff2283fdbe52ede48e69d0e20949a669c7bf2406bf4ace4","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:10:04.886Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"**Lane A: Fly.io Verdict**\n\nPick **Fly Machines + one Fly Volume** for v1. It’s the lightest option that still gives us real filesystem semantics for Git repos, GitMeta SQLite, file locks, and Rust code with `git` installed in the image.\n\nI’d run it as:\n\n```text\nagent-trail-generator.fly.dev\n  Rust HTTP worker\n  Docker image with git installed\n  one Machine\n  one mounted volume at /data\n```\n\nData layout:\n\n```text\n/data/\n  repos/github/<repo-id>.git\n  locks/<repo-id>.lock\n  state/agent-trail.sqlite\n  projections/<snapshot-id>.json\n  tmp/\n```\n\n**Why It Fits**\n\nFly Volumes are local persistent storage mounted into Fly Machines “like a regular directory,” backed by local NVMe on the same physical server. That is exactly what Git + `git-meta-lib` want. Source: [Fly Volumes overview](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/).\n\nThe single-writer story is actually a feature here: Fly says a volume attaches to only one Machine, and volumes do not auto-replicate. For us, that maps cleanly to “one generator owns the repo cache.” Source: [volume considerations](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/).\n\nRust worker deployment is straightforward: package the binary in Docker, deploy as a Machine, let Fly handle TLS/routing/process lifecycle. Source: [Fly Rust hosting](https://fly.io/learn/rust-hosting/).\n\n**Autostop Recommendation**\n\nFor v1:\n\n```toml\n[http_service]\nauto_start_machines = true\nauto_stop_machines = \"suspend\"\nmin_machines_running = 0\n```\n\nThat keeps costs low and preserves the volume. If we introduce background queue work where jobs continue after the HTTP request returns, change to:\n\n```toml\nmin_machines_running = 1\n```\n\nFly’s autostop/autostart docs are clear that `min_machines_running` keeps a primary-region Machine alive when autostop is enabled. Source: [autostop/autostart](https://fly.io/docs/launch/autostop-autostart/).\n\n**Backups**\n\nUse Fly’s daily volume snapshots and don’t over-engineer it. Repo caches are rebuildable. Fly keeps snapshots for 5 days by default, configurable 1-60 days, and supports on-demand snapshots. Source: [volume snapshots](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/snapshots/).\n\nFor anything non-rebuildable, like a future durable projection DB, export compact JSON/state to object storage too. Not v1 critical.\n\n**Gotchas**\n\nSingle Machine + single Volume means downtime on host trouble, deploy restarts, or migration. Fly explicitly says single Machine/Volume setups risk downtime/data loss and recommends multiple volumes for HA. Source: [volume redundancy](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/).\n\nVolumes are local, not network storage. You cannot mount the same cache into multiple Machines. Scaling horizontally means sharding repos across Machines/volumes or building replication. Don’t do that yet.\n\nVolume max is 500GB; can grow, cannot shrink. Start with maybe 20-50GB and implement repo cache pruning. Source: [volume size](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/).\n\nVolumes are not mounted during Docker build or release commands, so any cache/bootstrap logic must happen at app runtime. Source: [when volumes are unavailable](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/).\n\n**Recommendation**\n\nUse Fly for v1. It’s a good match because our problem wants local disk, not distributed storage. Start single-node, one writer, volume snapshots, cache pruning. Add HA only after Agent Trail proves it deserves the operational weight.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:10:04.886Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}